    <!-- Troubleshooting -->
    <div class="section" id="troubleshooting">
      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

      <div class="trouble-item">
        <h3>Wrong colours - image looks like a negative or has a red/blue swap</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>RGB565 byte order matters - try swapping the bytes in the converter</li>
          <li>In <code>image_to_rgb565.py</code>, change the val line to: <code>val = ((val &amp; 0xFF) &lt;&lt; 8) | ((val &gt;&gt; 8) &amp; 0xFF)</code></li>
          <li>This byte-swaps each pixel to big-endian order which some display configs expect</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="trouble-item">
        <h3>Compile error - array too large / out of memory</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Make sure <code>PROGMEM</code> is in the header - without it the 115KB array goes into RAM and overflows</li>
          <li>Check the generated <code>.h</code> file contains <code>PROGMEM</code> after the array declaration</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="trouble-item">
        <h3>Image draws but is shifted, tiled, or has garbage at edges</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>The image must be exactly 240x240 - check with <code>python3 -c "from PIL import Image; print(Image.open('myface.png').size)"</code></li>
          <li>Rerun the converter after confirming the source image dimensions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="trouble-item">
        <h3>Transparent areas showing as black or wrong colour</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Flatten the image in GIMP before exporting - <strong>Image &rarr; Flatten Image</strong></li>
          <li>Set your desired background colour before flattening</li>
          <li>The converter uses <code>.convert("RGB")</code> which drops the alpha channel - transparent pixels become black unless you flatten first</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="trouble-item">
        <h3>Display is blank after flashing</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Check the <code>#include "myface.h"</code> filename matches exactly - Arduino IDE is case sensitive on Linux</li>
          <li>Confirm the <code>.h</code> file is in the same folder as the <code>.ino</code> file</li>
          <li>Open Serial Monitor - if nothing appears, the sketch may have crashed on boot</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

  </main>
</div>

